<Document>
<name>Cameron Highlands Loop</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Cameron Highlands Loop</h2><p><i>Peninsular Malaysia · Pahang, Tapah to Simpang Pulai loop</i></p><p><b>Malaysia's tea country — colonial-era hill station at 1,500 m, BOH tea estates, mossy forest, strawberry farms.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>103 km (64 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>Full day; ideally 2–3 days</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>Year-round; cool any time (15–22 °C); driest December–March</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Rain almost daily; landslides in monsoon; tour bus traffic; tight switchbacks on the old Tapah road</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>221</td></tr></table><hr><p>The Cameron Highlands were charted in 1885 by surveyor William Cameron. Sir George Maxwell developed them as a hill station in the 1920s — a place where British colonial officials could escape Kuala Lumpur's heat to tea, scones, and 15 °C nights. Today the highlands are still cool (1,500 m altitude), still planted with tea (BOH and Bharat estates), and now also strawberries, vegetables, and flowers in millions of plastic-roofed greenhouses spread across the hillsides. The new road in from Simpang Pulai is fast; the old road from Tapah is slow and twisting and far prettier. The Mossy Forest at Gunung Brinchang is a 1,800 m cloud-forest of dwarf trees and pitcher plants in moss draperies — like nowhere else in Malaysia.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Tanah Rata</b> — Main highland village. Cameron Highlands Resort (1937) is the Tudor-style colonial centerpiece. The Jim Thompson Trail commemorates the American Thai-silk king who vanished without trace from a walk in these hills in 1967.</li><li><b>BOH Sungei Palas</b> — Largest of the BOH (Best of the Highlands) tea plantations, planted from 1929. Free factory tour ending at a tea-room cantilevered over the slope, where you drink the morning's pluck looking down the terraces.</li><li><b>Mossy Forest / Gunung Brinchang</b> — 2,032 m. A boardwalk on stilts winds through a cloud-forest where every branch and trunk is wrapped in moss, ferns, and pitcher plants. Open early morning before the cloud closes in.</li><li><b>Kampung Raja</b> — Wholesale market for the highland vegetable industry — Malaysia's brassicas, lettuces, and strawberries are largely from these greenhouses. Cabbages stacked into pyramids; the smell is overwhelming.</li><li><b>Ipoh</b> — Off the loop but worth the descent. Limestone hills riddled with cave temples (Sam Poh Tong, Kek Lok Tong, Perak Tong). Old-town heritage architecture; white-coffee street stalls; one of the great Malaysian food cities.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
